docs.lead_paragraph: In the three years since he took his final N.F.L. snap, Colin Kaepernick has said very little as he has remained a central figure in a national conversation about athletes and political speech. But soon, he will tell his side of the story at length.

docs.abstract: A new multimedia installation by Adam Pendleton, with live events daily, will explore the politics and aesthetics of blackness.
docs.snippet: A new multimedia installation by Adam Pendleton, with live events daily, will explore the politics and aesthetics of blackness.
docs.lead_paragraph: Adam Pendleton will transform the Museum of Modern Art’s atrium this summer into a theatrical stage set framed by three 60-foot-tall scaffolds displaying his work. The 36-year-old artist’s multimedia installation is titled “Who Is Queen?” and will be on view from July 25 through Oct. 4, with live daily events surrounded by text-based paintings, mobiles, video portraits and sound pieces exploring his concept of “Black Dada.”

headline.main: MoMA’s Atrium Set as Theatrical Stage for the Summer

docs.abstract: The heroine of Kate Chopin’s “The Awakening” begins to notice what she wants, rather than what her male-dominated society wants her to want.
docs.snippet: The heroine of Kate Chopin’s “The Awakening” begins to notice what she wants, rather than what her male-dominated society wants her to want.
docs.lead_paragraph: Early in “The Awakening” — Kate Chopin’s great feminist novel of identity and self-consciousness, which still throbs with relevance more than 120 years after its publication — the heroine’s husband picks a fight. He has spent the evening at a casino and now it’s approaching midnight, but the card game has left Léonce “in high spirits, and very talkative.” He wakes his wife to gossip but she answers him sleepily, “with little half utterances.” Spurned, and still intent on rousing her, Léonce manufactures a fever for their sleeping son. When Edna dares doubt this, Léonce calls her a bad mother. She springs out of bed to check, while Léonce — no longer worried, if he ever actually was — enjoys his cigar. Soon, Mr. Pontellier is fast asleep, but “Mrs. Pontellier was by that time thoroughly awake.”

headline.main: The Classic Novel That Saw Pleasure as a Path to Freedom

docs.abstract: Since 1900, the House and Senate have repeatedly failed to pass such a bill. Now the legislation could be on its way to the Oval Office.
docs.snippet: Since 1900, the House and Senate have repeatedly failed to pass such a bill. Now the legislation could be on its way to the Oval Office.
docs.lead_paragraph: Since at least 1900, members of the House and Senate have tried to pass a law making lynching a federal crime. The bills were consistently blocked, shelved or ignored, and the passage of time has rendered anti-lynching legislation increasingly symbolic.

headline.main: Congress Moves to Make Lynching a Federal Crime After 120 Years of Failure
